19/ Take the people with the right stuff. Give them funding, time, and trust. Goal on greatness, not Wall Street metrics.
18/ It's not true that all of the great products of our era have already been built.
17/ In the long term, only great products are defensible.
16/ Funding potential great products will often fail. The ones with the highest potential have the highest risk.
15/ Growth tactics only require short-term funding. Great products need time and trust for experimentation and learning.
14/ But if you decide between two projects to fund in the short term, the growth tactic will always look more appealing than great products.
13/ Growth tactics are fine as long as they are strapped to a fundamentally good product.
12/ That is the Silicon Valley equivalent of ruining the integrity of a generation of bright minds.
11/ Inexperienced people may be misled to define crappy metrics, then optimize against them for career points.
10/ Good people will also have the honesty and integrity to not game metrics if goaled on them.
9/ Good people feel if a product is winning or losing without having to look at metrics.
8/ All metrics of things that are actually valuable (quality, craftsmanship, word-of-mouth, total users) are mostly correlated.
7/ There is no single metric that will tell you if a product is good or not.
6/ Just because something is measured doesn‚Äôt mean it should be optimized.
5/ Just because something can be measured doesn‚Äôt mean it should be measured.
4/ Giving people with taste and leadership time and trust to build great products is the product development equivalent of Warren Buffett.
3/ Optimizing against Wall Street-reported metrics on a quarterly basis is the product development equivalent of day trading.
2/ They are not created by goaling on metrics on a quarterly basis. Especially if those metrics are reported to Wall Street.
1/ The great products of this world are created by combining long time horizons with taste and leadership.
